### NEW finding from this cycle ‚ÄĒ TGT-1 (Medium)

The gap-detection comparison on the target side is still
inclusive:

```python
# strategy.py:_target_exit_result
gap_through = bool(bar["Open"] >= target)   # long
gap_through = bool(bar["Open"] <= target)   # short
```

This is the same family of bug as NEW-2 on the STOP side, with
the same spec language ("opens beyond the target") implying
strict inequality. At `Open == target`:

- Current behaviour: gap_through=True, exit at `target` (no
  slippage).
- Spec-strict behaviour: gap_through=False, exit at
  `target - slippage` (long) / `target + slippage` (short).

I missed this during the previous review cycle when I asked for
the NEW-2 fix. The standing process I committed to says "apply
equality boundaries symmetrically across all comparisons that
share spec semantics" ‚ÄĒ exactly the case here.

Practical impact: floating-point exact equality on
`bar.Open == bar.SessionVWAP` is essentially never going to fire
on real data, but the principle and the standing process both
require the fix. The fix is two lines.

Fix:

```python
gap_through = bool(bar["Open"] > target)    # long
gap_through = bool(bar["Open"] < target)    # short
```

Test: an Open-equals-target equality-boundary test mirroring the
existing `test_generate_trades_treats_long_open_equal_stop_as_regular_stop`
pattern. Two tests, one per side.

Codex can land TGT-1 either:

- (a) bundled with the rest of the remaining audit follow-ups
  before 4c ‚ÄĒ preferred, since 4c will write decision-grade
  artifacts and any boundary inconsistency carries through.
- (b) as a separate small commit before 4c.

Either is fine. The point is: do not start 4c until this
spec-comparison drift is closed.

